=========================================
std::make_unique (C++14) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::make_unique?
----------------------------
- std::make_unique is a C++14 utility function.
- It creates an object and returns a std::unique_ptr to it.
- It is the recommended way to create unique_ptr.

Header:
#include <memory>

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Syntax
---------------
auto ptr = std::make_unique<Type>(constructor_args);

-----------------------------------------

3. Simple Example
----------------

#include <memory>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {

    auto p = std::make_unique<int>(10);

    cout << *p << endl;

    return 0;
}

-----------------------------------------

4. Why make_unique is needed?
-----------------------------
Before C++14:
We used:

std::unique_ptr<int> p(new int(10));

Problems:
- verbose
- error-prone
- unsafe in complex expressions

-----------------------------------------

5. Advantages of make_unique
----------------------------
✔ Exception safety (VERY IMPORTANT)
✔ No manual new/delete
✔ Cleaner syntax
✔ Prevents memory leaks in complex expressions
✔ Preferred modern C++ style

-----------------------------------------

6. Exception Safety Example
---------------------------

Problem with new:

foo(std::unique_ptr<int>(new int(10)), bar());

If bar() throws exception:
- memory leak can happen in complex evaluation order

Solution:

foo(std::make_unique<int>(10), bar());

✔ Safe: object created in controlled way

-----------------------------------------

7. make_unique vs new
---------------------

new:
- manual memory management
- error-prone
- not exception safe in complex calls

make_unique:
- automatic memory handling
- safer
- recommended

-----------------------------------------

8. make_unique vs make_shared
------------------------------

make_unique:
- single owner
- no reference counting
- lighter and faster

make_shared:
- shared ownership
- reference counting
- slightly more overhead

-----------------------------------------

9. Example with Class
--------------------

#include <memory>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Test {
public:
    Test(int x) {
        cout << "Constructor: " << x << endl;
    }
};

int main() {

    auto obj = std::make_unique<Test>(100);

    return 0;
}

-----------------------------------------

10. Array with make_unique
--------------------------

auto arr = std::make_unique<int[]>(5);

for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    arr[i] = i * 10;
}

-----------------------------------------

11. Why prefer make_unique in modern C++?
-----------------------------------------
- Safer memory management
- Avoids raw new/delete
- Exception-safe construction
- Clean and readable code
- Standard best practice

-----------------------------------------

12. Interview Key Points
------------------------
- Introduced in C++14
- Returns std::unique_ptr
- Preferred over new for unique_ptr creation
- Exception safe
- Cannot be copied (only moved via unique_ptr)
- Lightweight compared to shared_ptr

